## Project Rules and Conventions

This document defines the mandatory engineering rules for this repository. It complements PLAN.md and applies to all code (library, tools, and tests).

### Core principles

- Functional-first (F#): immutability by default, pure functions where practical, explicit inputs/outputs, small composable units.
- Railway-Oriented Programming (ROP): all domain workflows return `Result<'ok,'err>` or `Async<Result<'ok,'err>>`.
- Separation of concerns: data collection/IR is separate from visualization/rendering; no renderer-specific logic in traversal/IR.

### Result usage (mandatory)

- Use FSharp.Core `Result` and `Async<Result<_,_>>`. Do not introduce custom Result types.
- Prefer helpers in `ResultEx` for composition: `map`, `bind`, `mapError`, `bindError`, `apply`, `ofOption`, `sequence`, `traverse`, `tryCatch`, and `AsyncResult.*`.
- Do not use exceptions for control flow. Convert exceptions at boundaries via `tryCatch` into `Error` with rich context.
- Public APIs expose `Result`-based contracts; exceptions are allowed only for unrecoverable programmer errors (e.g., argument null in internal code paths).

### F# style (mandatory)

- Prefer pattern matching over `if/else` when matching cases or handling nulls/options/DU cases.
- Use options instead of nulls in internal domain types; convert input nulls to `option` at the edges.
- Naming: descriptive, readable; functions are verbs, values are nouns; no abbreviations if avoidable.
- Control flow: guard clauses and early returns; avoid deep nesting; keep functions small and focused.
- Comments: explain the “why”, not the “how”; avoid redundant comments; no TODOs—implement or create an issue.

### OpenAPI.NET v3.x specifics (mandatory)

- Use `Microsoft.OpenApi` v3.6+ APIs.
  - Prefer interfaces: `IOpenApiSchema`, `IOpenApiParameter`, `IOpenApiPathItem`, etc.
  - HTTP methods are `System.Net.Http.HttpMethod` (not `OperationType`).
  - Schema types are `JsonSchemaType` flags. Nullability is represented via `JsonSchemaType.Null` (no `Nullable` bool on schema).
  - Any/extension values are `JsonNode`/`JsonNodeExtension`. Use the JsonNode-based helpers in `OpenApiTools` (`tryGetValue`, `getExtensionValue`).
  - Content dictionaries use `IDictionary<string, IOpenApiMediaType>` (interfaces, not concrete types).
  - Readers: use `OpenApiDocument.Load/LoadAsync`. For YAML, register the YAML reader via `OpenApiReaderSettingsExtensions.AddYamlReader`.
  - References use `OpenApiSchemaReference` / `OpenApi*Reference` wrappers; do not assume concrete instances. Use adapter modules (`ReferenceAdapters`, `SchemaAdapters`) for null-safe decomposition.
  - Collections may be null—use `AdapterCore.ofObj`, `readMap`, `readSeq` for null-safe access.
  - Prefer the project's adapter modules (`OpenApiAdapterCore`, `OpenApiActivePatterns`, `SchemaAdapters`, `ReferenceAdapters`, `OperationAdapters`, `DocumentAdapters`, `ExtensionAdapters`) over direct null checks.

### Traversal & IR

- Traversal modules (`OpenApiTraversal`, `OpenApiOperationsTraversal`) must:
  - Work against interfaces (`IOpenApiSchema` etc.) and avoid unsafe casts.
  - Cover compositions consistently: `allOf`, `oneOf`, `anyOf`.
  - Gracefully handle cycles and visited caches.
  - Expose simple IR types for schema graphs and route maps; IR must be renderer-agnostic.

### Visualization (Graphviz)

- Graph rendering uses IR only. Rendering-specific styling stays in `Visualizing` projects.
- Schema node labels must include: name/title, type (`JsonSchemaType`), nullability (append `?`), format (when present), and for arrays “array of <ItemType>”.
- Route diagrams: base view is hub + routes (no HTTP verbs); options can add operations and referenced schemas.
- Keep diagrams readable: avoid noisy edge labels by default; provide options for verbosity when needed.

### Error handling & diagnostics

- Return `Error` with actionable messages and context (e.g., JSON pointer, path, or operation id).
- Avoid silent failures; prefer explicit error propagation via `Result`.

### Testing

- Unit tests: NUnit 4; property-based tests with `FsCheck` where valuable; snapshot tests with `Verify.NUnit` for DOT/SVG/IR outputs.
- Integration tests: end-to-end CLI tests should `dotnet build` the tool and then `dotnet run --no-build`.
- Tests must cover nullable handling, references, arrays, compositions, and large-spec edge cases.

### Performance & reliability

- Avoid unnecessary copies of OpenAPI models; prefer references and interface-based traversal.
- Keep allocations in hot paths low; avoid repeated parsing; cache visited schemas.

### Repo hygiene

- All PRs must be green: `dotnet build` and `dotnet test` for the solution.
- Follow these rules in code reviews; do not approve changes that violate ROP, Result usage, or F# style guidance above.


